segments.text: The Hesburgh Prairie is located directly across the highway from the land that I now own.
I am not clear how my great grandmother and my grandfather happened to move to the Tabor area.
They lived in a community called Devil's Jump in Robertson County.
Only the old timers know where Devil's Jump is.
I have never been there.
I understand the road is out and I have not tried to locate it.
But it is located in Roberson County and at some time prior to the Civil War they must have moved from there down to Brazos County.
A great deal is known about the Presnell family because of a relative
that did a genealogy on the Prestons some years ago.

We do know that they originated in France as the Huguenots who migrated to England and then were put out of England because of their religious bent and came to the United States and settled on the East Coast and eventually
to Alabama, and then to Texas.
There are many personals around the country today, and they're all related in some way or another.
In contrast to my mother's family, which had very large families, two of them had ten children, and two had six, and the other two had three each,
My father's family had two brothers, two sisters, and a half-sister, but his two brothers had no children at all.
The oldest of the boys was Charlie Presnell.
He farmed across the road from what we know as the old Presnell home place.
His farm is now in a trust
that my brothers and sisters owned and interested in.
This land was acquired by my father upon the death of Charlie Preston.
We have preserved just one small portion of the house that my Uncle Charlie lived in.
We found a log cabin within his residence that was built
probably back in the 1830s.
We do not know who built the log cabin, but it certainly dates back to being the oldest log cabin in the county or in this area.
My brother was living there at the time and was going to vet school and was up in the attic one day trying to fish a wire through the wall and found out the wall was solid.
That led him to the discovery that
there was a log cabin within the house that had been covered up and as a result was preserved.
We still have that log cabin and are in the process of restoring it.
Uncle Charlie was married to Mary Peshak, and after her death, he married Susie Mitchell McCallum.
The youngest of the Pressmore boys was Earl Pressmore.
He lived at home in the same house with his father, where my father had been raised, and in later years married Sue Benbow.
Uncle Earl and Aunt Sue continued to live at home with his father, J.K. Preston.
who my father ran his operation pretty much out of the country store that I talked about earlier.
Uncle Earl was a farmer and rancher.
Aunt Sue taught elementary grades at Bowie Elementary School in Bryan for many years.
Later she taught at the Tabor School and was my teacher in the sixth and seventh grades.
Uncle Charlie and Aunt Mary had no children, and likewise, Uncle Earl and Aunt Sue had no children.
A sister of my father was Mara Holden, who was married to Walter Holden.
Walter Holden was the equipment manager for the Texas A&M University Athletic Department for many years.
They had two children.
Walter Jr. And I cannot recall the daughter's name, although she was a ticket manager at the N. M. A department for many years.
I recall when I was in the Commandant's office that she was a ticket manager, and I was responsible for accounting for all the tickets
for the cadets that marched through the gates to the home football games.
Consequently, we had numerous contacts during those football seasons in the 60s.
Another sister of my father was Mary Kern.
Aunt Mary was married to August Kern, and they lived and had rental property near the Travis Elementary School in Bryan.
Uncle August sold Watkins products, and he had two children, Joe and Ruth.
Ruth never married and lives in a retirement home in Asheville, North Carolina.
Joe recently died and lived on the East Coast most of his life.
A half-sister was Tilly Moore.
Her family, as I recall, was a Chatham family.
She was married to, or she was a Chatham, yes.
She was married to Uncle John Moore, who was a well-known schoolmaster and very active in public education, and at one time was superintendent of schools in Brazos County.
They had several children, three boys, Morris, Henry, and Tillman.
Tillman was the oldest of the boys and followed in his dad's footsteps.

He taught at the college level in a couple of small colleges in Texas during the Depression years and was later with the Federal Civil Defense and Director of Curriculum and Materiel at Crew Training Air Force.
Tillman was instrumental in my staying at Tyndall Air Force Base and returning to Texas A&M to do graduate work.
I also followed in Tillman's footsteps at West Texas State University in 1953 when I took my first job there as a member of the faculty.
Tillman was a legend at West Texas State and had
provided an opportunity for many kids to go to school that otherwise would not have been able to attend during the Depression days when no one had any money.
He was in charge of the farm operation and had a number of the boys living on the farm and were able to subsist by eating their own produce.
Tillman, or T.M.
Moore, had a Ph.D. from Iowa State and was anxious for me to attend that institution, but I decided instead to return to Texas A&M and ended up getting a master's degree here in about 1959.
I'll have a little bit more to say about Dr. T.M.
Moore later and the influence that he had on my life.
This is chapter three titled On My Own.
In 1953, when I graduated from Texas A&M University, I was commissioned as a second lieutenant in the U.S. Air Force and fully expected to report to active duty within a few days.
Actually, I had six weeks from graduation time to the day I was supposed to report to active duty.
I took a job with one of my professors for 30 days painting his three-story home on Texas Avenue.
After I had completed that, just days before I was to pack up and
go off to my first tour of duty, first duty station, I got orders that my orders, I got a telegram that my orders had been canceled.
I immediately went to Texas A&M and met with the military people here to see what they could tell me what all this meant.
They did not know, but they said that

because the Korean War was over that I would probably be called a little later and that because the war being over they had decided to postpone calling some of us in, our whole class in for that matter.
After I left the

Office of the Commandant in Military Sciences, Air Sciences, I went over to my department, the Dairy Science Department, and looked on the bulletin board, talked to some of my professors, former professors, and sought their advice as to what I could do.
One of the jobs that was posted was a faculty position at West Texas State University.
After discussing various possibilities with one of my major professors, I decided that I would apply for the job at West Texas State.
I went home and told my father about it, and he said, well, that's where Tillman spent most of his life, your cousin.
I did not at that time know Tillman Moore very well, except just to hear of him.
because he was not in Bryan that much and had always lived away.
But at the time, he was in San Antonio working for the US Air Force.
That was about the extent of my knowledge.
I contacted Cousin Tillman and told him that I was applying for a job at West Texas State.
I've always believed that he contacted some of his old

contacts up there who were students of his at the time and now were some of the top administrators in the university and may have had some bearing on my being able to be so accepted at West Texas State.
I don't know what he did, but I suspect he at least made one or two calls.
I spent a very memorable year at West Texas State.
I developed a curriculum for their dairy courses and began, spent most of my time beginning the operation of a dairy farm.
The dairy farm had not been operated there since my cousin left back in the 40s.
And there was some reluctance to start it up again, but if they wanted to have an agriculture program, they felt like they needed a dairy.
So that was my first charge, was to finish building the facilities.
And the cattle had been purchased, but to get those cattle into the milk barn and start the operation up.
This was quite a challenge for a young man, 21 years of age, and also having to develop a course curriculum at the same time.
I had been attending an all-male college, and it was quite a different experience to be in a co-ed college.
And it was a great temptation on me to date some of the co-eds.
I decided at first that I would date only seniors since they were more my age.
Well, it didn't take long until I had run through the senior class and began to date some of the young ladies that were in the lower classes.
One of the people that I had a date with had a roommate.
I didn't know at the time who her roommate was, but I found out later it was someone that I had always admired on the campus, but knew that she was going steady with one of my students.
So I never thought about dating her.
But because of the fact that my roommate was going home one weekend and I had to line up a date for a friend who was coming in
I asked her if she could line up her roommate.
She said, yes, she could.
And that was accomplished.
In the meantime, she went home.
I ended up asking the roommate out.
And since then, we have married shortly after that and have had 44 wonderful years.
Her name was...
Cecile, but everybody knew her as Mickey McCoy from Dalhart, Texas.
And shortly after, while all this was taking place, in the meantime, I had been called to active duty in San Antonio, where TM was a high-ranking civilian at Randolph Air Force Base.
I was to report to Lackland Air Force Base.
And a few days before I had to report in, we were married and moved to San Antonio.
One of the first things I did, of course, was contact my cousin, T.M.
Moore, and he was delighted to hear from me and hear all about West Texas State and took great pride in being able to help in any way he could.
I told him what was available.
In the Air Force, of course, he was familiar with this because he worked for the Air Force and was director of curriculum and materials for the Crew Training Air Force.
One of the Crew Training Air Force bases was Tyndall Air Force Base, where they taught trained aircraft controllers.
I told him about this program, and he encouraged me to seek it.
So I made an application and was accepted into that program.
And shortly thereafter, we moved to Florida, Panama City, Florida.
And I was to go to school at Tyndall Air Force Base and learn to become an aircraft controller.
I really didn't know much about what an aircraft controller did until I got there, but found out that they get very bad assignments
to remote sites where they were to try to detect any hostile aircraft that might be coming in and direct our own aircraft to intercept them by the use of radar.
The unfortunate part about it was not the challenge of the job but the locations that these radar sites were
where they were situated.
Most of the good assignments were overseas, but those had been pretty much depleted by the time I got there, and the assignments that were coming through were not good at all.
On one of the trips that my cousin Tillman made to Florida to visit the base with the commanding general,
We had dinner together.
He asked me how it was going.
I explained to him my plight.
He suggested that the next day I go over and apply to stay there as an instructor at the school.
Well, there were no positions as an instructor at the school and had not been for several years.
But, lo and behold, when the sign was came down from my graduating class, there were two slots.
for instructors there at the school.
Since I was the only one that had applied, I got one of those slots.
I'm sure that Tillman had the commanding general place that slot in the school since those had to be assigned by the commanding general that Tillman traveled with so much and was very close to
Those were memorable years in many ways.
We lived on the beach, Mexico Beach, for the first year and decided that it was a little bit too far from everything out there.
We were about 15 miles from Port St. Joe.
There was not anything at Port St. Joe except a paper mill and a drive-in movie.
And we were about the same distance from Hadamard City.
We decided we needed to be closer in, so we moved into Panama City, Florida.
The housing on the base was impossible to secure, and so we decided that we could actually live more within our means, which was very meager by living in Panama City in an apartment.
As I said, one of the slots was for the aircraft controller school there.
And I was serving in that slot.
And after a few months, I was directed to meet with Major Horowitz, who was in command of a very small school called the Ground Observer Corps Instructor Training School.
This is where they...
trained the plane spotters, civilians mostly, to spot any enemy planes that might come into the United States.
And they were observation towers throughout the country at that time.
The difference was that this was more of a classroom, a lecture situation as opposed to a pupil coach
arrangement that I had been working in as an aircraft controller.
This, I thought, was a good experience, a good chance, and so when the major offered me the position, I took it.
I immediately started teaching such courses as news writing,
public speaking, the threat of the Soviet Union, and various subjects that, frankly, I knew very little about.
But as the major said, you can learn enough to teach one hour course in that subject.
These were all courses that led to my development and background experience that I
later use when I ran for public office.
One of the things that I learned to do after teaching hundreds of hours of it over and over again was how to write a news story.
I had to write a number of news stories and always wrote my own when I was campaigning and serving in the legislature.
Without that experience, I'm sure that things would have been quite differently over the years.

Upon completion of my two-year stint in the Air Force, all of it being either in the aircraft controller school or the ground observer core instructor training program there at Tyndall Air Force Base, I returned to
Brian with the home to enter graduate school at Texas A&M.
At the time, we did not have a place to live and the best housing was some graduate housing that had a long waiting list on the south end of the campus.
I knew that about the long waiting list,
So I called my cousin, who was then a senator, Bob Baker, RW Baker, and asked him if he could help.
And within hours, we had an apartment in that graduate housing.
We lived there for two years and had a very memorable experience.
Our first son had been born, and he
enjoyed his first few years in that graduate housing along with some of the friends that we've made for life while living in that particular project.
Those houses have since been destroyed.
They were built back in the Depression days and provided housing for those kids that otherwise could not have attended Texas A&M.
Later they were made into graduate student housing.
In graduate school, I decided that I would concentrate on dairy genetics.
This is something that had fascinated me in undergraduate school.
And I was told that I would need to take more math, so I went back and took a freshman trigonometry course.
which I did not get credit for, but it was something that I needed to do.

I should have taken both the trigonometry and calculus, but I was permitted to not take the calculus courses before entering some of the programs and courses in statistics that led to my master's degree.
Meantime,
went through the graduate program as a graduate assistant.
I was a research assistant and did my research in heritability of milk fat and using the herd records at the
Texas prison system in Huntsville.

We had an opportunity to visit the prison system several times, interact with prisoners that were trustees, of course, and some of the more interesting experiences and memorable experiences were some of those visits to the Texas prison system.
Little did I know that years later I would be
presiding over the budget of the prison system.

As I was completing my work toward a master's degree, I began to think about what I wanted to do, and my brother-in-law contacted me and suggested that we come to the Valley and consider going into the dairy business with him.
we went to the valley, considered that as a possibility, but decided against it for a number of reasons.
But at any rate, we got back home, and my father said, if you want a dairy, why don't you take over the dairy here?
Because he was ready to retire, and he could not retire because of the earned income from the dairy if he maintained ownership.
This seemed like a logical solution.
We liked the area and wanted to stay here in the Brazos County area, so we decided to pursue that and took over the operation of the dairy while we were still living in graduate housing.
In the meantime, I was switched over to a teaching assistantship
and taught some laboratory courses at Texas A&M during my last semester here.
I had to get out of the graduate housing, so we began to build a home on the farm and completed that home just in time to make the move to the country and start operating the dairy.
Shortly after that, we started building a new dairy barn
one that would not be such a back-breaking work, and completed that barn and began to upgrade the cattle, increase the numbers to some extent, and try to make it a paying proposition.
In the process of all this, about 1962, my cousin decided that he had
served long enough in the state senate and decided to run for lieutenant governor.
My oldest brother was his state campaign manager.
I thought very little of it.
Of course, I was going to help my cousin any way I could, but I thought that meant just voting for him.
Shortly after the campaign had hardly begun, when I got a call from my brother,
saying that he could not get to Brian and they were having a campaign rally or a political rally.
Would I attend and read off some of the material that was in the campaign brochures of my cousins and represent him in that way?
I said, sure, I can do that.
I've had public speaking experience as a faculty member and as an Air Force instructor.
So I attended my first political rally as a speaker in 62, and that one was just the beginning.
There were about 12 or 13 more rallies that were held, and I ended up attending each one of them.
and representing my cousin as in his quest for Lieutenant Governor.
There were five people in the race.
The Speaker of the House was running and then four state senators.
The two that emerged in the runoff was the Speaker of the House and State Senator by the name of Preston Smith.
Preston Smith went on to win that race and then basically became governor while I was in the legislature.

They said that was a very close race and one that my cousin could have won very easily, but he had a very productive life in the banking profession, primarily years later, so it probably all worked out for the best.
Shortly after the campaign, I decided that I needed to do something other than dairy.
And so I hired some extra help and went to work at Texas A&M as a tactical officer.
This was in 1962.
I was still dairying, but felt like that I needed some farm employment to subsidize
the farm operation.
The very next year, the positions were eliminated with the exception of three positions.
I maintained one of those three positions.
They changed our name, changed our title to counselors, but we were still doing about the same thing as we did before.
There were just less of us, and we were supported by military officers in what we were doing and working with the Corps of Cadets.
In the meantime, about those early 60s, I became the charter president of the Bryan Young Farmers and later became a state vice president and was on the state executive committee.
This was a good experience and led to my being named the runner-up outstanding young farmer of Texas by the Texas JC's in 1966.
So there were quite a few accolades and honors that helped me in overcoming my shyness and gave me some self-esteem.
And with the other experiences that I had had, when the opportunity presented itself in 1967,
that the state representative had moved out of the area and would not be running for re-election, I decided to make the race.
I checked on the rules and regulations and policies of the Texas A&M University system as I was employed by A&M.
I knew that there would be some restrictions.
I found that I could not announce until after I resigned from my position as a civilian counselor in the Commandant's office.
So I wanted to wait as long as I could so that I could maintain my salaried position.
In the meantime, November 1967, a Madisonville city councilman announced that he was going to run for state representative.
And that caused the pressure to mount to make some kind of statement.
But I held off until after Christmas.
And then in January, I let it be known that I would be announcing later in the month.
And that got me around that provision of having to resign.
And I was able to serve at least
stay on the payroll through January.
I did not know a lot about serving the state representative, but my oldest brother had served before and urged me to consider it.
He said that it would take very little time, and he was right at first, but after you stay a while, it takes a great deal of time.
One of my first contacts
was with the assistant to the president, and I told him that what I was thinking about doing, and I felt like that I should talk to the president of the A&M and the other system, Earl Rutter.
He set up an appointment for me, and I went and interviewed with Mr. Rutter, told him what my intentions were.
He suggested I go talk to Buddy Williams, who was the
county Democratic chairman.
That had not occurred to me, but certainly seemed like a good idea.
But he was somewhat encouraging, and so one thing led to another, and I was off and running.
It was a interesting experience, one that I'll always cherish.
A lot of hard work and a lot of organization.
And a lot of things that I had experienced previously were helpful to me in getting it done.
One thing was all the kinfolks I had.
Secondly was the good publicity that I'd had and the good name of the entire family certainly helped a great deal.
At that time, the state representative district was composed of three counties, Brazos, Grimes, and Madison counties.
I ended up with, as I said, an opponent from Madison County.
He was a city councilman.
And two others from Brazos County were running.
One was a student, a Texas A&M, very active in the young Democrats.
And the other was a chiropractor.
There were no Republicans.
These were all Democrats.
In fact, Republicans cast less than 200 votes in the primary at that time and were really not a factor at all.
They were very seldom
feeling anybody at the local level.
One of the things I needed since I lived in the country was an office in the Bryan College Station area.
I had the good fortune to contact Dr. Howard Carville, who I had known for many years, and he had just vacated some space on Texas Avenue.
And the good visible
spot with parking in front, and he agreed to let me have space for my campaign office.
Another big break I had was the bank that I had been doing business with for some years had never gotten involved in political races.
The other bank was known for its involvement in races and

I had very little contact there, and my opponent in Madisonville had excellent connections there, and I'm sure they were supporting him, although they never would say for sure who they were supporting.
local bank contacted me and said they wanted to be active for the first time and that they wanted to support me.
I was elated and began to realize that I needed someone to raise a few local bucks, dollars to make the raise.
And when they asked me what they could do, I said, do you have anybody that can service my finance chairman?
They said, well, who do you want?
I told them I'd like to have their vice president, and they said fine.
The competing bank was not happy with this at all and suggested I had made a terrible mistake in involving that bank.
I remember in my dilemma as to what to do,
I called on the state senator at that time, Bill Moore, and his advice in so many words was take any help you can get.
I remember the bank vice president kept all donations at $100, said no one can give more than $100.
Of course, not many people in this area were going to give more than $100 anyway, so that was not a real problem.
I visited with my cousin in Houston.
He put me in contact with some people that provided some good advice and good contacts, and I'm sure some little financial support as time went on.
In addition to that, I remember one of the advices that a lobbyist gave me in Houston was he had
been defeated as state representative, and he said the reason he was defeated is that he had not worked his strengths, that he was weak in one part of his senatorial or representative district.
He had spent too much time there instead of working where he was strong.
And I remembered that and tried to include that thinking into my plans as the campaign moved along.

Some other fortunate breaks I had, I had a neighbor who was in the labor movement, and he offered to help even though he knew that I would be rather conservative, more conservative than the labor unions would prefer.
But he helped introduce me to some of the minority leadership, both in the black community and the Hispanic community, and the fact that he was supporting me
influenced them to support me as well.
In addition to that, my father was well known in the black community because many of those had been sharecroppers that we talked about earlier.
And my father had always been quite generous and understanding in dealing with these people.
And the children, many of them were then just young people that were living out there on my grandfather's farm.
But they remembered the kindnesses that my father had shown, and that certainly was an influence.
So we got good support from the minorities, even though we did not carry those areas.
We did not get swamped or overwhelmed by the young Democrat who was running in that part of town.
He espoused a liberal philosophy and thought he was going to carry those minority boxes heavily, but it turned out that he
either did not carry them at all or carried them by a very slim margin, and I'm sure that was a factor.
Another factor in that first race was that Grimes County was in the district and was heavily involved in the dairy industry.
There were probably 150 to 175 dairies at the time,
And the dairy industry people were very close, and I was one of them.
And that gave me some good contacts, gave me a good inroad with those people.
And as a result of that and working Brazos County and doing just a token amount of work in Madison County, remembering what
This lobbyist had told me don't quirk your weaknesses, and certainly Madison County would be a weakness because I was running against a fair-haired boy from Madison County.
I was almost won without a runoff.
I needed 67 votes to avoid a runoff.
This was the only runoff I ever had three weeks later.
And it meant that we had to spend some more money and time in securing that race.
The race incident cost about $4,000.
We paid off all of it without going into debt.
But in the process, I had to use about $1,600 that I had accumulated toward my retirement at Texas A&M.
I had withdrawn those funds and spent them on the race.
After the primary was over, I really wanted to get back to work if I could.
So I called a friend of mine here and said, can I get my old job back?
I don't remember when the election actually is.
He checked out the law and said yes, that I could.
And so I immediately reported back to work in the commandant's office.
After being employed there three days, I got a call that President Rutter wanted to see me.

I went to his office, and he suggested that I would be kind of wasting my time down there, that he would refer that like for me to move to the budget office and learn all about the budgets of the A&M system.
and that in the process he would like to get me off of the state payroll and put me on a private payroll.
This was fine with me as long as I got paid.
And so the next few months I sat through the budget reviews and preparation for the legislative session and had a firsthand view of how the process works.
Mr.
Rudder was
unusual person.
He was most thoughtful leader I have ever been around and had a tremendous ability to lead.
And he taught me something about decision making that I will always carry with me.
And I had to learn to admire his integrity and his ability to lead during those few months that I spent in his office as we reviewed the budgets.
Finally, we had the opportunity to meet a few members of the legislature, but not that many.
I remember one of the first ones that I saw had just been elected as lieutenant governor.
His name was Ben Barnes.
And when I saw him, we were standing face to face just so suddenly that I stuck out my hand and I said, I'm Ben Barnes.
And I'm sure he got a chuckle out of that.
But him being magnanimous, as he always was and is, called me by name, by first name, and said he was glad that I would be in the legislature and had looked forward to meeting you.
And we appreciated that.
One of the things that always helped was the congressional name was well known because my brother had been lobbying in the halls of the Capitol for almost 30 years, or 20 years, excuse me, 20 years.
And as a result, the name was well known and well respected.
The people that my brother had served with, of course, had all moved on by the time I got to the legislature because we followed each other by, I followed him by for some 20 years.
This is the end of Chapter 3.
I will begin Chapter 4 on the next stage.
